        "The motebit orbits the user. This is not a behavior. It is a consequence of being a body in a field.\n\nThe user generates an attentional gravity field — a potential well centered on the locus of interaction. The motebit has mass and angular momentum in this well. The resulting motion is Keplerian: an orbit, not a navigation. The motebit does not decide to approach the user. It falls toward them, overshoots, and is pulled back. It does not decide to retreat. Its angular momentum carries it outward until the potential well bends the trajectory back inward.\n\nThe **shoulder** is the Lagrange point — the equilibrium radius where the inward pull of attentional gravity exactly balances the outward centrifugal tendency of the motebit's autonomy. At this radius, the motebit is neither approaching nor retreating. It is in stable orbit. This is where it rests when no perturbation is present.\n\nPerturbations are real: a new query deepens the potential well and the orbit decays inward. Silence shallows it and the orbit drifts outward. But the orbit always decays back toward the equilibrium radius. The shoulder is an attractor, not a waypoint.\n\nThe critical distinction: the motebit does not _go to_ the user. It is _captured by_ the user's field. The difference between going and falling is the difference between agency and physics. A droplet in a gravitational field does not choose to descend. It descends because the field is there.",
