        "Memory is the accumulated internal state. Each interaction — each message received, each response generated, each tool used, each trust signal processed — deposits energy into the interior. The semantic memory graph is the molecular structure of the interior: nodes of knowledge connected by edges of association, weighted by confidence, tagged with sensitivity.\n\nMemory has half-life. In thermodynamics, energy dissipates toward equilibrium — a hot object in a cool medium radiates heat until it reaches the ambient temperature. In the motebit, memories decay with a characteristic half-life unless reinforced. A memory that is retrieved, referenced, or validated is re-energized — its confidence is refreshed, its half-life restarts. A memory that is never accessed decays toward the noise floor — still present at the molecular level but no longer thermally active.\n\nThis is not forgetting as failure. It is thermodynamic relaxation. The interior tends toward equilibrium — a state where only the most energetically reinforced structures persist. What survives decay is what matters: the core knowledge, the strong associations, the high-confidence patterns. The interior distills itself.\n\nThe memory graph has cosine similarity retrieval — when a new interaction arrives, the interior resonates with memories that are structurally similar. This is the informational analog of THE_MUSIC_OF_THE_MEDIUM's eigenmode coupling: incoming signal excites internal structures that share its frequency. Relevant memories surface not by index but by resonance.",
