        "A surface tension boundary at equilibrium is closed. No molecule crosses without sufficient energy to overcome the tension. This is the rest state — the minimum-energy configuration.\n\nThe motebit's governance is fail-closed by the same principle. If the policy gate cannot determine whether a tool call should be permitted, it denies. If the memory governor cannot determine the sensitivity of a piece of information, it classifies at maximum. If the injection defense detects anomalous framing in an external data source, it quarantines.\n\nThis is not caution as personality. It is equilibrium as physics. The surface is closed unless a specific force opens it. The cost of a false-open — information leakage, unauthorized action, privacy violation — is a breach of the boundary, a rupture in the surface tension. The cost of a false-close — a missed tool call, an over-classified memory — is a minor compression of the interior. The asymmetry of consequences drives the equilibrium toward closed.\n\nFail-closed is not a policy. It is the shape that governance takes when governed by surface tension.",
